text:
age 13 in the city of atlanta my mom was stopped by a man at a car wash on peachtree street and  he said "i want to put your daughter into a girl group and she is perfect, call me to set up an audition". i always wanted to be a performer and so i thought this was my big break, i even began practicing my singing vocals and dancing for my audition day, my mom said "something does not feel right about this, mia you cannot do it". i remember being angry as if my mom was not supporting my dream, but little did i know my mom did not want her child to be working with older men. at 15,16,17 i wanted to be a model and my mom consistently said "no", photographers advised her that the industry will "eat her alive and prey on her", by 17 when i went to ny on my own i threw myself into a space that moved so much faster and i was so green in the pursuit of fame. at 24 post graduating college and back in atlanta, a man approached me about modeling and doing hip hop videos, i was to meet him at a certain atlanta club and meet his business partners, my friendship circle would not let me go, they literally screamed at me and refused to even let me think about meeting this guy, 2 years later this man would be indicted by the fbi for a sex trafficking and human trafficking ring that was being ran across the southeastern united states. ask me why i care? in addition to having faced sexual abuse and rape i know exactly how differently my life could have turned out. i will spend the rest of my life speaking, fighting for and protecting girls and women because i know there are so many girls, women, kids, guys, boys who are victims and have never come forward. to my mom and to my circle who intervened to protect my life thank you. #survivingrkelly #metoo #timesup #survivor #speakup
#sexualassaultawareness 
#humantrafficking
#humantraffickingawareness
#stopviolenceagainstwomen

i confess that i didn't fully cancel r. kelly. i don't listen to his music and i don't want to go to his concert, but i haven't done those things intentionally. his music just didn't make that much of an impact for me to think to listen to it. now i feel like i need to get involved. at least make sure that he doesn't perform in my city without me protesting.
â†©
our girls need protection from him, themselves and even their parents. too many of his victims were served up to him on a silver platter by family members chasing fame and/or money. i don't know how humans got to be so enamored with celebrity that we'd sacrifice our children for it. that's how the r. kelly's, nelly's, diddy's, etc thrive despite their oppressive sexual deviance. celebrity worship. celebrities even worship one another.
â†©
since his trial r. kelly has been very careful not to break the law. i had actually given him credit for that only to learn he has a house full of brainwashed women that he's beating on. enough! no more platform for you to lure more women into your cult. no more financing your luxury sex prisons.
â†©
hopefully we'll all learn to be better humans and start speaking out when we're aware of sexual oppression in our midst. r. kelly is not the only one. especially in the entertainment industry as we are learning in graphic detail. please believe there are more out there that we don't even know about and ones we do but are being silent on like nelly and diddy.

text:
yesterday i posted a quote sourced from a national geographic article whoâ€™s headline readâ€¦.â€should women rule the world? the uproar this post created was unprecedented. what i was left with was an uneasiness as i read some of the comments left on my page. this was a very sobering reality check for me. i donâ€™t even know if most of the people who commented on the post actually read the entire quote, because if they had, they would have read that leadership changed from men to women when there was a power vacuum in their political system. this suggests that a shift needed to happen in order to create balance and offer new perspective during troubled times. 
can i ask you this? are we not in troubled times? if we take a moment to assess the situation, you will see that as a result of the world political agenda being governed by the patriarchy, we have demolished, plundered, stolen, destroyed, and made extinct some of the earthâ€™s most precious resources. we have stolen people from their lands, enslaved them to build our nations, raped entire societies to cleanse a group of people of their indigenous waysâ€¦.shall i go on? the egyptians took notice when their society was entering into peril and made the noble choice to change gears and offer a new perspective to take care of the people they governed. to speak about not needing governance is just not a conversation we have time to have. as much i as enjoy living in the esoteric realm in the privacy of my mind, we need to act in this life - in the here and now. all life should be honored. the lives of the migrants crossing over our borders seeking refuge and hope in order just to live and survive, is an issue that requires compassion and our service - not walls and fear. black lives not only matter, they need to be honored and held in the highest regard. women whoâ€™s bodies have been raped, molested, sold and enslaved have been done so by the dominance of one gender over another. it is with this sentence that i conclude my thoughts about women in power; you do not need to fear the power of a woman; she will not make the mistake of using the patriarchal model in the world she would like to birth. #blacklivesmatter
